In my opinion it&#39;s unnecssary in this case, but this is for the reason if `current.classList.remove(&#39;current&#39;)` won&#39;t be executed the code inside `setTimeout(() =&gt; current.classList.remove(&#39;current&#39;));` will be executed last. This is just like an insurance. Look at the short theory:

    console.log(&#39;One&#39;);
    setTimeout(()=&gt;console.log(&#39;Two&#39;));
    console.log(&#39;Three&#39;);
 
    The console logs: One, Three, Two.
This happens because code inside setTimeout is sets to the callback queque and will be executed only if stack will be empty, because setTimeout is an async function. (setTimeout is a Web API function so, after being in the stack and before being in the callback queque will be pushed to the Web API box)

